Availability zones.

An availability zone, or A-Z, is one or more discrete data centers, each with its own power, cooling, and physical security. A region has three to six of them, named by a suffix: U-S-east-one-a, U-S-east-one-b, U-S-east-one-c, and so on.

Two properties make them useful. First, they sit tens of miles apart, far enough that a single fire or flood can't take more than one of them. Second, they're joined by high-bandwidth, low-latency fiber, so the network between them is fast and effectively local. Far enough apart to fail independently, close enough to act as one.

That combination is the foundation of high availability on AWS. Running across two or three availability zones inside a region means that a single data center failure doesn't take your service down. Anywhere you meet the term multi-A-Z in AWS, whether it's R-D-S Multi-A-Z, an auto scaling group spread across zones, or a load balancer balancing across zones, this is the principle at work.
